EMBARGO ENFORCEMENT: THE OPERATIONS ARE BEING CONDUCTED IN SUPPORT OF THE EMBARGO IN THE MARITIME SURVEILLANCE AREA (MSA) ENCLOSED BY THE FOLLOW POINTS, CLOCKWISE FROM POINT A: A. 34-00N 012-00E, B. 34-00N 022-00E, C. 33-00N 025-00E AND THEN DIRECTLY SOUTH TO LIMIT OF LIBYAN TERRITORIAL WATERS AND THEN FOLLOWING LIMIT OF LIBYAN TERRITORIAL WATERS WESTWARDS TO LIMIT OF LIBYAN TERRITORIAL WATERS AT 12-00E DIRECTLY SOUTH OF POINT A. THE MSA IS IDENTICAL TO THAT DEFINED IN THE CANCELED HYDROLANT 587/11. 3. REPORTING SYSTEM: ALL VESSELS PLANNING TO TRANSIT THROUGH THE MSA ARE REQUIRED TO SEND THE DATA SPECIFIED TO THE NATO SHIPPING CENTRE (UK) AND TO NATO HQ MC NAPLES, 12 HOURS BEFORE ENTERING THE MSA. DATA TO SEND: A. SHIP NAME. B. FLAG. C. IMO NUMBER. D. INMARSAT PHONE NUMBER. E. SHIP'S CURRENT POSITION AND TIME OF SENDING MESSAGE. F. CURRENT COURSE. G. CURRENT SPEED. H. CARGO. I. DESTINATION AND ESTIMATED DATE AND TIME OF ARRIVAL. J. LAST PORT CALLED AT, AND THE DATE AND TIME OF DEPARTURE FROM THAT PORT. 4. GENERAL GUIDANCE FOR MARINERS: NATO NAVAL UNITS WITHIN THE MSA WILL HAIL AND MAY BOARD VESSELS. WILLINGNESS TO COOPERATE AND QUICK RESPONSE TO HAILING WILL MINIMIZE DELAYS TO MERCHANT SHIPPING TRAFFIC. FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION, A DEDICATED NATO NAVAL COOPERATION AND GUIDANCE FOR SHIPPING (NCAGS) TEAM CAN BE CONTACTED DIRECTLY 0430Z TO 1630Z AT NATO HQ MC NAPLES. THE NCAGS TEAM'S ROLE IS TO ENHANCE COORDINATION BETWEEN NATO UNITS ENFORCING THE EMBARGO AND MARINERS TRANSITING THE MSA. ALSO, THE NATO HQ MC NAPLES MARITIME OPERATION CENTRE (MOC) CAN BE CONTACTED 24 HOURS A DAY. NATO HQ MC NAPLES RECOMMENDS THAT MERCHANT SHIPPING COMPANIES WITH VESSELS PLANNING TO CALL AT LIBYAN HARBORS CONTACT THE NCAGS TEAM AT NATO HQ MC NAPLES. 5. PANAMA CANAL. 1. MULTI-NATION NAVAL CONTROL OF SHIPPING (NCS) AUTHORITIES WILL BE CONDUCTING AN EXERCISE FROM 19-24 AUGUST 2011. THE EXERCISE WILL BE ONGOING IN THE BROAD VICINITY OF APPROACHES TO THE PANAMA CANAL. 2. AN NCAGS REGION WILL BE DECLARED EFFECTIVE AS OF 19 AUGUST IN THE INTERNATIONAL AND COASTAL WATERS APPROACHING THE PANAMA CANAL, BOTH ATLANTIC AND PACIFIC. A MULTI-NATIONAL COALITION NAVAL FORCE AND NOTIONAL RISK AREAS WILL BE PRESENT IN THESE WATERS. THE REGION WILL BE DISESTABLISHED AS OF 24 AUGUST 2011. 3. MERCHANT AND COMMERCIAL SHIPS TRANSITING THESE AREAS MAY BE REQUESTED TO REPORT VESSEL INFORMATION UTILIZING FORMAT ALPHA REPORTING FORMAT AS OUTLINED IN ALLIED TECHNICAL PUBLICATION ATP2(B) VOL 2- NAVAL CO-OPERATION AND GUIDANCE FOR SHIPPING MANUAL (NCAGS)- GUIDE TO OWNERS, OPERATORS, MASTERS AND OFFICERS. BASIC INFORMATION INCLUDES: A. SHIP NAME B. CALLSIGN/IMO# C. E-MAIL ADDRESS OF VESSEL D. TYPE OF SHIP (E.G. TANKER, CONTAINER, BULK, FISHING.) E. TYPE OF CARGO F. POSITION, COURSE AND SPEED AT TIME OF REPORTING G. PREVIOUS PORT OF CALL H. NEXT PORT OF CALL SHIP INFORMATION WILL BE HANDLED AS BUSINESS AND SECURITY SENSITIVE INFORMATION. REPORTS DURING THE EXERCISE SHOULD BE MADE TO THE SHIPPING COORDINATOR AT THE FOLLOWING E-MAIL ADDRESS: SCT@NAVYTELEX.US 4. SAFETY IS PARAMOUNT. THE EXERCISE WILL NOT EMPLOY ACTUAL CHANGES TO MARSEC LEVEL OR SHIPBOARD EMERGENCY ALERT SIGNALS. NAVAL GUIDANCE TO MERCHANT SHIPPING IS ADVISORY ONLY. MERCHANT PARTICIPATION IS STRICTLY VOLUNTARY. 5. MERCHANCT VESSELS INTERESTED IN VOLUNTARY EXERCISE PARTICIPATION DURING THE EXERCISE PERIOD SHOULD CONTACT JECG@NAVYTELEX.US. THE HIGHEST CONSIDERATION FOR VOYAGE SCHEDULES AND EFFICIENCIES IS RECOGNIZED. AS PRACTICAL, NCAGS WILL ASSIST DOCUMENTATION OF SHIP PARTICIPATION FOR SECURITY DRILL PURPOSES. 6. VESSELS WITHIN THE NCAGS SHIPPING AREA DURING THE EXERCISE DATES WITH QUESTIONS OR CONCERNS CAN CONTACT THE PANAMA LOCATED NCAGS SHIPPING CONTROL TEAM (SCT) VIA E-MAIL TO: SCT@NAVYTELEX.US. 7. FOR FURTHER INFORMATION REGARDING THIS ADVISORY, CONTACT CAPTAIN ROBERT FORD, MARITIME ADMINISTRATION, OFFICE OF SECURITY, CODE: MAR-420, ROOM W25-308, 1200 NEW JERSEY AVE, S.E., WASHINGTION, DC 20590, PHONE: 202 366 0223, FAX: 202 366 3954, TELEX: 7108229426 (MARAD DOT WSH) OR E-MAIL: MARADSECURITY@DOT.GOV. 8. CANCEL THIS MSG 25 AUG.

COMMAND AND CONTROL OF NATO MARITIME EMBARGO OPERATION NATO HAS ASSUMED THE ROLE OF COORDINATOR FOR THE MARITIME EMBARGO OPERATIONS IN VICINITY OF LIBYAN ARAB JAMAHIRIYA (LIBYA) IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE UNITED NATION SECURITY RESOLUTION (UNSCR) 1970 AND 1973. THERE CONTINUES TO BE A LARGE NUMBER OF NAVAL VESSELS OPERATING IN THE AREA. 2. MARITIME SURVEILLANCE AREA (MSA) AND MARITIME INTERDICTION OPERATIONS (MIO) ARE CONDUCTED IN THE MEDITERRANEAN SEA AND SYSTEMATICALLY ENFORCED IN THE FOLLOWING MARITIME SURVEILLANCE AREA (MSA): A. NORTHERN LIMIT: 34-00N B. WESTERN LIMIT: 34-00N 012-00E C. SOUTHERN LIMIT: LIBYA TTW LIMIT (NOT INCLUDED) D. EASTERN LIMITS: 34-00N 022-00E AND 33-00N 025-00E 3. REPORTING SYSTEM IN ORDER TO REDUCE TO A MINIMUM THE DISRUPTIONS TO MERCHANT TRAFFIC, THIS EMBARGO IS RUN USING A SYSTEM BASED ON THE DISTANCE OF A M/V FROM THE MARITIME SURVEILLANCE AREA AND THE VESSEL'S NEXT PORT OF CALL (NPOC). THE REPORTING SYSTEM IS UPDATED AS FOLLOWS: ALL M/V PLANNING TO TRANSIT THROUGH THE MSA WILL SEND A FORMAT A (REF ATP 2(B) IS AVAILABLE AT: HTTP:WWW.SHIPPING.NATO.INT) MESSAGE TO THE NATO SHIPPING CENTRE (UK) 12 HOURS PRIOR TO ENTERING THE MSA. UPON ENTERING THE MSA, VESSEL WITH A NPOC IN LIBYA MUST SEND AN ADDITIONAL FORMAT MESSAGE TO THE NATO HQ MC NAPLES (ITALY). ALL M/V LEAVING A LIBYAN HARBOUR WILL SEND A FORMAT MESSAGE TO THE NATO HQ MC NAPLES SIX HOURS PRIOR TO SAILING FROM THE HARBOUR. TRANSMISSION CHANNELS REMAIN THE SAME: E-MAILS, PHONE CALL ETC. CF PARA 5. 4. GENERAL GUIDANCE FOR MARINERS: NATO IS ENFORCING THIS ARMS EMBARGO AND WILL BE PROACTIVE IN MEASURES TO DETERMINE A VESSEL'S CARGO AND NPOC. NATO NAVAL UNITS ARE FULLY COMPLYING WITH INTERNATIONAL LAWS AND CONVENTIONS. MERCHANT SHIPS IN COMPLIANCE WITH THE ARMS EMBARGO HAVE NO REASON TO FEAR NATO NAVAL UNITS. WILLINGNESS TO COOPERATE AND QUICKLY RESPOND TO NATO UNIT HAILING IS HIGHLY ENCOURAGED IN ORDER TO MINIMIZE DELAYS TO TRAFFIC FLOW. A NAVAL COOPERATION AND GUIDANCE FOR SHIPPING (NCAGS) CELL CAN BE CONTACTED 24/7 ( 24 HOURS / 7 DAYS PER WEEK) IN THE HEAD QUARTERS MARITIME COMMAND (HQ MC) NAPLES-MARITIME OPERATIONS CENTRE (MOC). THIS CELL'S MAIN TASK IS TO ENHANCE COORDINATION BETWEEN NATO UNITS ENFORCING THE EMBARGO AND MARINERS TRANSITING THROUGH THE MARITIME SURVEILLANCE AREA. HQ MC NAPLES STRONGLY RECOMMENDS TO MERCHANT COMPANIES PLANNING THEIR SHIPS TO CALL IN LIBYAN HARBOURS TO LIAISE FIRST WITH NCAGSCELL. 5. POINTS OF CONTACT: THIS OPERATION IS CONDUCTED BY THE NATO HEADQUARTERS MARITIME COMMAND LOCATED IN NAPLES, ITALY. IT'S MARITIME OPERATIONS CENTER IS THE MAIN POINT OF CONTACT FOR ANY ISSUE OR INFORMATION REGARDING THE ARMS EMBARGO: HQ MC NAPLES MOC PHONE: 800 1101 2010. HQ MC NAPLES MOC UNCLASSIFIED INTERNET ADDRESS: MOCN3DOGCELL@MANP.NATO.INT FOR OTHER ISSUES, THE NATO SHIPPING CENTRE (NORTHWOOD, UNITED KINGDOM), REMAINS THE MAIN POC, PHONE: 44 192 395 6574, FAX: 44 192 395 6575, E-MAIL: INFO@SHIPPING.NATO.INT. 6. EASTERN MEDITERRANEAN SEA. LIBYA. 1. IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE UNITED NATIONS SECURITY COUNCIL RESOLUTION 1970 (26/02/2011) AND 1973 (17/03/2011), NATO MARITIME FORCES ARE CONDUCTING ARMS EMBARGO OPERATIONS IN THE VICINITY OF LIBYA TERRITORIAL WATERS. 2. THOSE OPERATIONS ARE CONDUCTED IN THE MEDITERRANEAN SEA AND SYSTEMATICALLY ENFORCED IN THE FOLLOWING MARITIME SURVEILLANCE AREA: A. NORTHERN BORDER: THE 35N PARALLEL. B. WESTERN BORDER: TUNISIAN TERRITORIAL WATERS (NOT INCLUDED). C. EASTERN BORDER: EGYPTIAN TERRITORIAL WATERS (NOT INCLUDED). D. SOUTHERN BORDER: LIBYAN TERRITORIAL WATERS (NOT INCLUDED). 3. ALL MERCHANT VESSELS TRANSITING IN THIS AREA OR INBOUND TO LIBYA TERRITORIAL WATERS MAY BE SUBJECT TO HAILING, QUERIES OR BOARDING FROM NATO NAVAL AND AIR UNITS. ALL MERCHANT VESSELS TRANSITING THROUGH THIS MARITIME SURVEILLANCE AREA ARE REQUESTED, 24 HR PRIOR THEIR ENTERING IN THIS AREA, TO CONTACT THE NATO SHIPPING CENTRE (UNITED KINGDOM, CONTACT DETAILS BELOW): EITHER VIA PHONE, FAX OR E-MAIL TO PROVIDE A FORMAT ALFA REPORT. THE REPORT MUST INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION: A. IMO NUMBER. B. DTG. C. POSITION, SPEED AND COURSE. D. LAST PORT OF CALL. E. NEXT PORT OF CALL. F. PORT OF REGISTRY. ALTERNATIVELY, A FORMAT ALFA FORM (REF ATP 2(B) IS AVAILABLE AT: (HTTP:WWW.SHIPPING.NATO.INT). ALSO, ALL MERCHANT VESSELS INBOUND TO LIBYA TERRITORIAL WATERS ARE REQUESTED, WHEN CROSSING THE BOUNDARIES OF THE MARITIME SURVEILLANCE AREA, TO CONTACT THE HEAD QUARTERS MARITIME COMMAND, NAPLES, MARITIME OPERATIONS CENTRE (ITALY, CONTACT DETAILS BELOW): EITHER VIA PHONE, FAX OR E-MAIL TO PROVIDE THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION: A. IMO NUMBER. B. LAST PORT OF CALL. C. NEXT PORT OF CALL. D. PORT OF REGISTRY. 4. THIS REQUEST FOR REPORTS FULLY SUPPORTS THE EMBARGO OPERATIONS UNDER THE UNITED NATIONS SECURITY COUNCIL RESOLUTION AND IS, THEREFORE, MANDATORY. THIS MEASURE IS COMPLEMENTARY OF THE ACTION OF NATO NAVAL FORCES IN THE VICINITY OF LIBYA TERRITORIAL WATERS. NATO PRIORITY IS TO REDUCE INTERFERENCES AND DELAYS CAUSED TO MERCHANT SHIPPING TRAFFIC TO ITS MINIMUM. IT IS THEREFORE HIGHLY RECOMMENDED FOR MERCHANT VESSELS TRANSITING THROUGH THIS AREA TO COOPERATE PROMPTLY WITH NATO FORCES. CONSEQUENTLY, FAILURE TO COMPLY WITH THAT GUIDANCE WILL RESULT IN FURTHER INVESTIGATIONS CONDUCTED BY NATO NAVAL UNITS. THIS INVESTIGATION WILL INCLUDE DETAILED QUERIES, BOARDINGS OR EVEN DIVERSION TO NEARBY PORTS FOR INSPECTION AND WILL CAUSE MAJOR TRANSIT DELAYS TO MERCHANT SHIPPING. 5. POINTS OF CONTACT: THIS OPERATION IS CONDUCTED BY THE NATO HEADQUARTERS MARITIME COMMAND LOCATED IN NAPLES, ITALY. IT'S MARITIME OPERATIONS CENTER IS THE MAIN POINT OF CONTACT FOR ANY ISSUE OR INFORMATION REGARDING THE ARMS EMBARGO: HQ MC NAPLES MOC PHONE: 00 800 1101 2010. HQ MC NAPLES MOC UNCLASSIFIED INTERNET ADDRESS: MOCN3DOGCELL@MANP.NATO.INT 6. REMINDER: HQ MC NAPLES IS ALREADY CONDUCTING OPERATION ACTIVE ENDEAVOUR, NATO OPERATION AGAINST TERRORISM IN THE MEDITERRANEAN SEA. THE MOC CAN ALSO BE CONTACTED REGARDING THIS ISSUE: HQ MC NAPLES MOC OPERATION ACTIVE ENDEAVOUR COLLECT PHONE: 39 081 1970 6533. 7. FOR OTHER ISSUES, THE NATO SHIPPING CENTRE (NORTHWOOD, UNITED KINGDOM), REMAINS THE MAIN POC, PHONE: 44 192 395 6574, FAX: 44 192 395 6575, E-MAIL: INFO@SHIPPING.NATO.INT.

EASTERN MEDITERRANEAN SEA. LIBYA. 1. COALITION FORCES ARE CONDUCTING MILITARY OPERATIONS IN SUPPORT OF AN ARMS EMBARGO, NO-FLY ZONE AND OTHER MISSIONS TO PROTECT THE CIVILIAN POPULATION IN LIBYAN ARAB JAMAJIRIYA, AS AUTHORIZED BY UNITED NATIONS SECURITY COUNCIL RESOLUTION (UNSCR) 1973 IN THE MEDITERRANEAN SEA AND GULF OF SIDRA IN AN AREA BOUND BY 33-08-00N 011-32-00E, 33-19-00N 011-13-00E, 34-12-38N,011-12-25E, 35-35-55N 011-31-35E, 36-30-00N 011-10-00E, 36-30-00N 022-00-00E, 33-45-00N 025-09-00E, 31-40-00N 025-09-00E. EXCLUDING THE LAND AND TERRITORIAL SEAS OF THE REPUBLIC OF MALTA. 2. NAVAL VESSELS ARE CONDUCTING OPERATIONS IN INTERNATIONAL WATERS AND LIBYAN ARAB JAMAJIRIYA TERRITORIAL SEAS AND MAY POSE A HAZARD TO NAVIGATION. ALL VESSELS ARE ADVISED TO EXERCISE EXTREME CAUTION WHEN SAILING IN THE VICINITY OF, OR INTO OR OUT OF, THIS DESIGNATED AREA. 3. IN ACCORDANCE WITH PARAGRAPH THIRTEEN OF UNSCR 1973, MEMBER STATE MILITARY FORCES ARE AUTHORIZED TO INSPECT VESSELS IN THE TERRITORY OF LIBYAN ARAB JAMAJIRIYA, INCLUDING SEAPORTS, AND ON THE HIGH SEAS BOUND TO OR FROM THE LIBYAN ARAB JAMAJIRIYA IF THERE IS INFORMATION THAT PROVIDES REASONABLE GROUNDS TO BELIEVE THAT THE CARGO CONTAINS ARMS AND OTHER MATERIEL, THE SUPPLY, SALE, TRANSFER OR EXPORT OF WHICH IS PROHIBITED BY PARAGRAPHS NINE AND TEN OF UNSCR 1970 AS MODIFIED BY UNSCR 1973. 4. VESSELS FOUND TO BE CARRYING PROHIBITED ITEMS BOUND TO OR FROM LIBYAN ARAB JAMAJIRIYA ARE SUBJECT TO DETENTION AND THEIR CARGO SUBJECT TO SEIZURE. 5. FURTHER, COALITION FORCES ARE CONDUCTING MILITARY OPERATIONS IN THIS AREA IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE AUTHORIZATIONS STATED IN PARAGRAPHS FOUR AND EIGHT OF UNSCR 1973. VESSELS TRANSITING THESE WATERS DO SO AT INCREASED RISK. THE TIMELY AND ACCURATE IDENTIFICATION OF ALL VESSELS AND AIRCRAFT IN THE OPERATION AREA IS CRITICAL TO AVOID THE INADVERTENT USE OF FORCE. ALL VESSELS ARE ADVISED THAT COALITION FORCES ARE PREPARED TO EXERCISE SELF-DEFENSE MEASURES AS MAY BE NECESSARY TO ENSURE THEIR SAFETY IN THE EVENT THEY ARE APPROACHED BY VESSELS OR AIRCRAFT WHOSE INTENTIONS ARE AMBIGUOUS. COALITION FORCES ARE PREPARED TO RESPOND DECISIVELY TO ANY HOSTILE ACTS OR INDICATIONS OF HOSTILE INTENT. ALL MARITIME VESSELS OR ACTIVITIES THAT ARE DETERMINED TO BE THREATS TO COALITION FORCES WILL BE SUBJECT TO DEFENSIVE MEASURES, INCLUDING BOARDING, SEIZURE, DISABLING, OR DESTRUCTION, WITHOUT REGARD TO REGISTRY OR LOCATION. 6. ALL VESSELS SHOULD MAINTAIN A SAFE DISTANCE FROM NAVAL VESSELS CONDUCTING MILITARY OPERATIONS IN SUPPORT OF THE ARMS EMBARGO, THE NO-FLY ZONE, AND OTHER MISSIONS TO PROTECT THE CIVILIAN POPULATION IN LIBYAN ARAB JAMAJIRIYA SO THAT INTENTIONS ARE CLEAR AND UNDERSTOOD BY THE NAVAL FORCES. ALL SURFACE VESSELS, ALL SUBSURFACE VESSELS, AND ALL AIRCRAFT APPROACHING COALITION FORCES ARE REQUESTED TO MAINTAIN RADIO CONTACT ON BRIDGE TO BRIDGE CHANNEL VHF 16, INTERNATIONAL AIR DISTRESS (121.5 MHZ VHF) OR MILITARY AIR DISTRESS (243.0 MHZ UHF).

GULF OF ADEN RED SEA. HORN OF AFRICA. 1. THIS MARAD ADVISORY PROVIDES INFORMATION ON THE RISK TO VESSELS TRANSITING THE HIGH RISK WATERS OF THE GULF OF ADEN (GOA), RED SEA, THE INDIAN OCEAN, ARABIAN SEA AND WATERS OFF THE HORN OF AFRICA (SOMALIA). 2. THIS ADVISORY WILL BE PUBLISHED ON THE MARAD WEB SITE AT WWW.MARAD.DOT.GOV UNDER THE HORN OF AFRICA PIRACY PORTAL AND ON THE U.S. COAST GUARD HOMEPORT SITE AT HOMEPORT.USCG.MIL/PIRACY. OTHER PERTINENT INFORMATION IS ALSO POSTED ON THESE WEB SITES. 3. U.S. FLAG OPERATORS WITH SHIPS IN THE AFFECTED AREAS ARE REQUESTED TO FORWARD THIS ADVISORY TO THEIR SHIPS BY THE MOST EXPEDITIOUS MEANS. 4. U.S. FLAG SHIPS OPERATING IN HIGH RISK WATERS ARE REQUIRED TO COMPLY WITH U.S. COAST GUARD MARITIME SECURITY (MARSEC) DIRECTIVE 104-6 (CURRENT VERSION). GUIDANCE, ADVISORIES AND LINKS TO ASSIST U.S. FLAG VESSELS IN COMPLYING WITH THE MARSEC DIRECTIVE AND IN COMBATING PIRACY MAY BE ACCESSED ON HOMEPORT AT HTTP://HOMEPORT.USCG.MIL/PIRACY. QUESTIONS MAY BE DIRECTED TO LCDR JAMES FOGLE, U.S. COAST GUARD, PHONE: 202 372 1038, E-MAIL: JAMES.T.FOGLE@USCG.MIL. NONE OF THE GUIDANCE IN THIS NOTICE IS MEANT TO SUPERCEDE MARSEC DIRECTIVE 104-6 (CURRENT VERSION) OR SUPPORTING PORT SECURITY ADVISORIES. 5. PIRATES ARE ATTACKING VESSELS, INCLUDING YACHTS AND RECREATIONAL CRAFT, IN THE GULF OF ADEN, OFF THE SOMALI COAST AND IN THE INDIAN OCEAN. ATTACKS HAVE OCCURRED OVER 1000 NAUTICAL MILES AWAY FROM SOMALIA, OFF THE COAST OF OMAN AND IN THE ARABIAN SEA LESS THAN 200 MILES FROM THE COAST OF INDIA. ATTACKS HAVE ALSO TAKEN PLACE OFF THE KENYAN AND TANZANIAN COASTS, SOUTHERN RED SEA, SEYCHELLES, MALDIVES, MADAGASCAR AND AN ATTACK IN THE MOZAMBIQUE CHANNEL. THESE PIRATES ARE FIRING AUTOMATIC WEAPONS AND ROCKET PROPELLED GRENADES (RPG) IN AN ATTEMPT TO BOARD AND HIJACK VESSELS. ONCE THE ATTACK IS SUCCESSFUL AND THE VESSEL HIJACKED, THE PIRATES DIRECT THE VESSEL TO THE SOMALI COAST AND THEREAFTER DEMAND RANSOM FOR THE SAFE RELEASE OF THE VESSEL AND CREW. PIRATES HAVE INCREASINGLY USED HIJACKED FISHING VESSELS AND MERCHANT VESSELS TO CONDUCT PIRACY OPERATIONS AS MOTHER VESSELS TO SAIL FAR FROM THE SOMALI COAST TO ATTACK AND HIJACK PASSING VESSELS. SMALLER SKIFFS ARE LAUNCHED FROM THE PIRATE MOTHER VESSEL TO ATTACK THE MERCHANT VESSELS. PIRATES ARE HEAVILY ARMED WITH AUTOMATIC WEAPONS AND RPGS. 6. DESPITE THE INCREASE IN PRESENCE AND EFFECTIVENESS OF NAVAL FORCES IN THE REGION, AS WELL AS THE EFFECTIVENESS OF DEFENSIVE AND PROTECTIVE MEASURES, PIRATE ACTIVITY HAS CONTINUED AND COMMERCIAL AND CIVILIAN SHIPS CONTINUE TO BE ATTACKED AND SEIZED. 7. TRANSIT BY YACHTS AND PRIVATELY OWNED SAILING VESSELS THROUGH HIGH RISK WATERS IS EXTREMELY HAZARDOUS AND MAY RESULT IN CAPTURE BY PIRATES. VESSELS THAT MAKE THIS PASSAGE DESPITE THIS WARNING SHOULD MAKE CONTACT IN ADVANCE WITH THE NAVAL AUTHORITIES. IN ADDITION, AMERICAN CITIZENS ABOARD SHOULD INFORM THE NEAREST U.S. EMBASSY OR CONSULATE OF THEIR PLANS TO TRANSIT THE AREA AND/OR UPDATE THEIR INFORMATION VIA THE SMART TRAVELER ENROLLMENT PROGRAM (STEP) ON WWW.TRAVEL.STATE.GOV. BASIC GUIDANCE FOR TRANSIT CAN BE FOUND AT HTTP://WWW.MSCHOA.ORG/YACHTINGGUIDANCE/PAGES/ YACHTINGGUIDANCEONE.ASPX. IF YOU ARE DUE TO TRAVEL THE AREA OF HIGH THREAT, PLEASE INFORM MSC(HOA) BY E-MAILING POSTMASTER@MSCHOA.ORG WITH THE SUBJECT LINE "YACHT VESSEL MOVEMENT". 8. RELATED COAST GUARD NOTICE: THE U.S. COAST GUARD RECENTLY ISSUED A NOTICE TO MARINERS ADVISORY FOR YACHTS AND SAILING VESSELS. THE COAST GUARD ADVISES THAT YACHTS AND SAILING VESSELS ARE PARTICULARLY VULNERABLE TO ATTACK DUE TO THEIR LOW SPEED AND LOW FREEBOARD. THE COAST GUARD ADVISES AGAINST ALL OPERATION OF OR TRAVEL BY YACHT AND PLEASURE CRAFT ON THE HIGH SEAS IN THE GULF OF ADEN, ARABIAN SEA, SOMALI BASIN AND THE WESTERN PARTS OF THE INDIAN OCEAN. ALL YACHTS AND SAILING VESSELS INTENDING TO SAIL THROUGH HIGH RISK AREAS SHOULD RECONSIDER THE NECESSITY OF THEIR TRAVEL AND ALTERNATIVES, SUCH AS TRANSPORTING THE VESSEL BY YACHT CARRIER. THE COAST GUARD FURTHER ADVISES THAT PARTICIPANTS IN YACHT RACES AND RALLIES IN THESE HIGH RISK AREAS ARE AT GREAT RISK OF ATTACK. THESE EVENTS ARE OFTEN PUBLICIZED AND COULD DRAW ATTENTION FROM PIRATES, DESPITE THE SECURITY AND SAFETY MEASURES THAT MIGHT BE PUT IN PLACE. THE COAST GUARD STRONGLY URGES MARINERS NOT TO PARTICIPATE IN THESE EVENTS THAT WILL REQUIRE TRANSIT THROUGH HIGH RISK WATERS. FOR THE TEXT OF THE COAST GUARD NOTICE, PLEASE GO TO HTTP://HOMEPORT.USCG.MIL/PIRACY. 9. HOWEVER, AMERICAN CITIZENS ABOARD YACHTS AND SAILING VESSELS SHOULD INFORM THE NEAREST U.S. EMBASSY OR CONSULATE OF THEIR PLANS TO TRANSIT THE AREA AND/OR UPDATE THEIR INFORMATION VIA THE SMART TRAVELER ENROLLMENT PROGRAM (STEP) ON WWW.TRAVEL.STATE.GOV. 10. VESSELS SHOULD REGISTER FOR ACCESS TO MSCHOA WEBSITE AT HTTP://WWW.MSCHOA.ORG TO OBTAIN UP TO DATE INFORMATION OF THE CIRCUMSTANCES AND CONDITIONS IN THE REGION. 11. FOR FURTHER INFORMATION REGARDING THIS ADVISORY, CONTACT CAPTAIN ROBERT FORD, MARITIME ADMINISTRATION, OFFICE OF SECURITY, CODE: MAR-420, ROOM W25-308, 1200 NEW JERSEY AVE, S.E., WASHINGTON, DC 20590, PHONE: 202 366 0223, FAX: 202 366 3954, TELEX: 710 822 9426 (MARAD DOT WSH) OR E-MAIL: MARADSECURITY@DOT.GOV.
